{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631528","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631528"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:28:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:28:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17382"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17382"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10072"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115113"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10072","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10072"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17382"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97121"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7772"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23573"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23576"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115113"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher is studying factors that influence blood pressure. They collect data on age, body mass index (BMI), daily sodium intake, and physical activity levels from 200 participants. They plan to analyse how these variables together predict systolic blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the key advantage of using multiple linear regression for this analysis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Requires only categorical independent variables","Eliminates the need for assumptions about data distribution","Determines causation between variables","Accounts for measurement error in variables","Allows examination of multiple predictors while controlling for confounding effects"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe key advantage of multiple linear regression is that it \u003Cstrong\u003Eallows examination of multiple predictors while controlling for confounding effects\u003C/strong\u003E. This means we can assess the unique contribution of each independent variable (age, BMI, sodium intake, physical activity) to systolic blood pressure while accounting for the influence of other variables in the model.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple linear regression can handle both continuous and categorical predictors\u003C/strong\u003E, not just categorical variables. \u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple linear regression requires several assumptions including normality of residuals and homoscedasticity\u003C/strong\u003E, so it does not eliminate the need for assumptions about data distribution. \u003Cstrong\u003ERegression shows association but cannot establish causation\u003C/strong\u003E without appropriate study design. \u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple linear regression actually assumes variables are measured without error\u003C/strong\u003E rather than accounting for measurement error.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMultiple linear regression produces a coefficient for each predictor, representing its relationship with the outcome while holding other variables constant. The overall model fit is assessed using R\u00b2, which indicates the proportion of variance explained by all predictors combined.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Multiple linear regression analyses the relationship between a continuous dependent variable and multiple independent variables simultaneously.","The regression coefficient for each independent variable represents its unique contribution while controlling for other variables in the model.","The coefficient of determination (R\u00b2) indicates the proportion of variance in the dependent variable explained by all independent variables together."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004.","Motulsky H. Intuitive Biostatistics: A Nonmathematical Guide to Statistical Thinking. 4th ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press; 2017. Chapter 37; pg. 378."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97121"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17382"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97121"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-22T11:43:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-22T11:43:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10072"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115113"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (int